<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> How to Avoid the Sharp End of the Knife<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.44)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1149'>Drew "Player27" Lichtenstein</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1149&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 13, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> *NOTE: None of the new Mines of Moria cards are reflected in this article*<br />
<br />
The game is unbalanced towards the free people. I mean, yes, they have powerful cards that defeat minions, but from a strictly card by card basis and the mere rules of the game, the shadow has the upper hand. As the fellowship player your goal is to keep Frodo alive. It doesn&#8217;t really matter if your deck is meant to win by overwhelming their ring-bearer and just go one site at a time, if your opponent wears down your fellowship and leaves Frodo vulnerable to skirmishes, your in trouble. For the majority of non-Hobbit decks, the way to keep Frodo safe through site nine is to keep your fellowship safe so the shadow player has more they have to break through to succeed in their task.<br />
<br />
Going back to the first statement, it&#8217;s important to recognize why the shadow player has an upper hand on you. The first reason is probably the most painfully obvious: they even up at the end of each turn but you only do so if you&#8217;re not going to double move. This means there&#8217;s always that inherit risk in the double move or in the simple fact that the shadow player doesn&#8217;t HAVE to wear you down to the point of death at a single site. All a shadow player has to do to slow you down is simply drop one or two big minions (Troop of Uruk-Hai, Witch King, Goblin Patrol Troops) and leave enough in the pool with the threat of more at the next site. Sure, the Witch King will probably just wound Arwen twice, but with a companion already exhausted and you having to face a fourteen strength minion twice again at your next site, your need to want to move a second time is severely lowered. On the flip side, as the fellowship, losing companions hurts. A lot. A deck can&#8217;t stand to lose more than a couple (read: not Pippin) companions in a game before it finds itself in a hole. <br />
<br />
The other minor (or major, depending on how you look at) issue for the free people is the fact that the shadow wins ties in skirmishes. While its minor enough, its annoying because the Scavengers that just pulled back a Scimitar for themselves are now equal in strength to Aragorn with his Sword. However, is it worth it to fill your deck with strength boosters? They can clog up your hand during your shadow phase, causing you to have to more or less rely on the power of your fellowship to win. However, if your opponent faces a weak shadow side because your hand is clogged up with strength boosters and not minions, they&#8217;ll most likely double move quite a bit, making it extremely difficult to win the race to site nine.<br />
<br />
With the inherit strengths of the shadow side aside, how can the free people beat this to guarantee that Frodo has some companions left when they reach site nine? While there&#8217;s many things involved, for the free people, the five main things to focus on are: focus, manipulation, direct damage, healing, and defense.<br />
<br />
Focus is key for any fellowship to do well. Sure, you could just throw on all the big mains (Aragorn, rare Boromir, Arwen, Legolas, Greenleaf, etc&#8230;) but you lack some major focus. Boromir&#8217;s special skill is one of the most powerful in the game, but without some Armor, he&#8217;ll still be ripped to shred by Uruk-Hai. Legolas, Greenleaf&#8217;s ability is huge, but with no other forms of archery or direct damage to back him up, he&#8217;ll never anything bigger than a Moria Scout. Also, the other key to focus is making sure that you&#8217;ll never be stuck with cards you don&#8217;t need, causing your shadow side to be weakened. Defiance is a great card against the Nazgul, but with no Arwen out your just wasting space. Really, for almost all intents and purposes, your starting fellowship and maybe your site one (or a companion who you run a lot of) should be the focus of your deck. Focus will also add one other key thing to your deck: twilight denial. If your just focusing on loading Aragorn up or just on using Gandalf to clear the sites, you won&#8217;t be adding not needed twilight and, in turn, will mean less minions that you face on a site to site basis. So, in reality, the question ask yourself is the following: which is better, a fellowship that is disorganized and handing out twilight like candy or one that is focus with tough companions and, once it gets going early on, adds little to the pool?<br />
<br />
Manipulation and card drawing are more focal to the shadow player since they&#8217;ll need the constant diet of minions to throw at the free people, but its also a key aspect to the free player. Drawing those key cards (Power According To His Stature, Aragorn&#8217;s Bow, etc&#8230;) at the right time can make or break the difference in any game. I&#8217;m an avid fan of discard shadow cards during reconciliation during the shadow turn and free people&#8217;s cards during the free people&#8217;s turn. Unless its something insanely useful, there&#8217;s almost no way at all it will find use during the opposite side&#8217;s turn. At the very least, it lets you clear throw some of the junk in your deck and get down to what you need. More directly, forms of discarding and drawing cards are always nice (such as Elrond), but, as the free people, you must be careful of giving off high amounts of twilight for a card who&#8217;s uses may end up being limited (such as Elrond).<br />
<br />
Killing minions is hard. I mean, the smallest minion at the current time has five strength and the biggest fifteen, with a higher-than-your--average-fellowship-member&#8217;s strength average in the middle. Direct damage is one of the most consistent ways to make sure that your opponent&#8217;s minions won&#8217;t remain. Think about why archery is so good: for the cost of exertion or sometimes nothing, you get the ability to cause wounds without risking a skirmish. Even if you aren&#8217;t running archery (it&#8217;s very heavily metated against with Spies of Saruman), it&#8217;s important to have some ways to hurt minions so a double move or avoiding skirmished all together can be easier. A Ranger&#8217;s Versatility is one of the most effective cards in the game for this, but don&#8217;t forget something like Blade of Gondor or Gondor&#8217;s Vengeance which can kill or wound minions with little cost. Even something as minor as damage +1 (which many weapons give) can be efficient enough for slowing down an opponent&#8217;s mid-ranged vitality minions.<br />
<br />
Healing is absolutely vital to winning. Beyond the sanctuary at site six, its really all or nothing when it comes to skirmished, with no one roaming. Since the twilight pool is high, your more likely to incur many more wounds and healing every single one off mean your Arwen or Boromir can survive for an extra turn, even if it just means they&#8217;ll bite the dust the next turn, its better than Frodo or your souped Aragorn doing it. Aragorn, King In Exile is the best way to do this, but since Aragorn, Ranger of the North has powerful defender +1 text, have other methods based on your deck prepared. Athleas is huge since it lets you heal at any site and get rid of pesky Nazgul conditions. Gandalf is great for healing with Strength of Spirits (doesn&#8217;t really heal but saves exertions until absolutely necessary) and Sleep, Cardahas letting you clear off damage inducing condition, such as Worry and Under The Watching Eye. Some decks, such a the Hobbit Healing Circle, are totally bent on keeping your companions alive by healing. Regardless of how you play it, it is imperative that there is some form of healing in all of your decks (or condition removal) or you&#8217;ll be stuck between a rock and a hard place.<br />
<br />
The final major aspect the free people&#8217;s player should make sure they run is defense. Lets face it, you can&#8217;t win them all: the Cave Troll is always a tough guy to stop and the Witch King doesn&#8217;t normally brake for anyone. Cards like Pippin and Tharin are powerful for a reason: for little cost they can jump in skirmishes instead of someone else, causing your opponent to grimace when they see their hard earned twilight pool simply go to the cause of crushing your Hobbit or Dwarven shield. Some shields, like Boromir, Lord of Gondor, will stay longer then others, while other, like Sam, are good for a one time use and then being crushed. Also, defense isn&#8217;t always just taking bullets for the team, but also using cards like the Hobbit Stealth: avoiding skirmishes can be just as good as fighting them. Either way you look at it, it&#8217;s very important to make sure that you don&#8217;t lose companions until early on and the best way to do this is to throw cards like Pippin and Tharin in front of those hungry Cave Trolls.<br />
<br />
It sounds difficult to be the fellowship player, right? Twilight denial, focusing on one or two characters, skirmishing, double moving, healing, direct damage, defense, offense, etc&#8230; The reality is that a good player can start to add these aspects without a second, with versatile cards easily filling up multiple gaps in a deck. It just takes time and practice, but tuning and playing can make these skills second nature to almost any player.<br />
<br />
See you at the end,<br />
<br />
-Drew<br />
